OUTPUT_DIR <- "/home/ec2-user/scitoseq/results/semiNMF_comparison"
results_list <- readRDS(file.path(OUTPUT_DIR, "all_estim_results.rds"))
print(results_list[[1]]) # v1_zscore_masked
plot(results_list[[1]], main = "V1 zscore masked")

print(results_list[[2]]) # v2_zscore_unmasked
plot(results_list[[2]], main = "V2 zscore unmasked")

print(results_list[[3]]) # v3_lfc_masked
plot(results_list[[3]], main = "V3 lfc masked")

print(results_list[[4]]) # v4_lfc_unmasked
plot(results_list[[4]], main = "V4 lfc unmasked")

# summary statistics
for (version_name in names(results_list)) {
  estim_r <- results_list[[version_name]]
  
  if (!is.null(estim_r)) {
    cat(sprintf("\n%s:\n", version_name))
    
    # Extract metrics
    if (inherits(estim_r, "NMF.rank")) {
      # Get cophenetic correlation
      coph <- estim_r$measures$cophenetic
      disp <- estim_r$measures$dispersion
      
      # Find optimal rank (max cophenetic)
      best_rank_coph <- RANK_GRID[which.max(coph)]
      
      cat(sprintf("  Best rank (cophenetic): %d (coph = %.3f)\n", 
                  best_rank_coph, max(coph)))
      cat(sprintf("  Cophenetic range: %.3f - %.3f\n", min(coph), max(coph)))
      cat(sprintf("  Dispersion range: %.3f - %.3f\n", min(disp), max(disp)))
    }
  } else {
    cat(sprintf("\n%s: FAILED\n", version_name))
  }
}
@

v1_zscore_masked:
  Best rank (cophenetic): 5 (coph = 0.839)
  Cophenetic range: 0.617 - 0.839
  Dispersion range: 0.173 - 0.495

v2_zscore_unmasked:
  Best rank (cophenetic): 5 (coph = 0.848)
  Cophenetic range: 0.634 - 0.848
  Dispersion range: 0.168 - 0.482

v3_lfc_masked:
  Best rank (cophenetic): 5 (coph = 0.870)
  Cophenetic range: 0.614 - 0.870
  Dispersion range: 0.231 - 0.431

v4_lfc_unmasked:
  Best rank (cophenetic): 5 (coph = 0.852)
  Cophenetic range: 0.607 - 0.852
  Dispersion range: 0.266 - 0.511
  
  
Cophenetic correlation measures the stability of the factorization across multiple runs. Higher values indicate more reproducible clustering — the sample assignments remain consistent when you rerun the algorithm with different initializations. This is often considered the most important metric for rank selection in NMF-type analyses.
Dispersion quantifies the spread of entries in the consensus matrix. Higher dispersion means samples are more clearly assigned to one cluster versus another (entries closer to 0 or 1 rather than intermediate values). It complements cophenetic correlation as a stability measure.
Explained variance (evar) is the fraction of total variance in the original data captured by the factorization. It increases monotonically with rank (more components = more variance explained), so on its own it always favors higher ranks.
Residuals and RSS (residual sum of squares) both measure reconstruction error — how well W×H approximates the original matrix. Both decrease with increasing rank. Like evar, these always improve with more components, so you're looking for an "elbow" where improvement plateaus.
Silhouette measures how well-separated the resulting clusters are. Higher silhouette scores (for coefficients/consensus) indicate that samples within each cluster are more similar to each other than to samples in other clusters. The coefficients (green) and consensus (purple) silhouettes can diverge.
Sparseness measures how concentrated (sparse) the basis vectors and coefficients are. Sparser solutions are generally more interpretable, as each component captures a distinct, localized signal.


